// LC Accounting Walkthroughs Data (auto-generated)
var WALKTHROUGHS_ACCOUNTING = {
  "2022": [
    {num:1, label:"Q1A: Company Final Accounts - Manufacturing (McGuigan Ltd)", q:"McGuigan Ltd has an authorised capital of \u20ac2,000,000 divided into 1,500,000 ordinary shares at \u20ac1 each and 500,000 4% preference shares at \u20ac1 each.\n\nTrial balance extracted on 31/12/2021 includes:\n- Plant and machinery (cost \u20ac340,000): \u20ac290,000\n- Factory buildings (cost \u20ac890,000): \u20ac865,000\n- Stocks: Raw materials \u20ac27,300, WIP \u20ac38,650, Finished goods \u20ac38,400\n- Direct factory wages: \u20ac148,000\n- Purchase of raw materials: \u20ac760,400\n- Sales: \u20ac1,650,000\n- 8% Debentures (incl. \u20ac50,000 issued 01/04/2021): \u20ac300,000\n- 4% Investments acquired 01/04/2021: \u20ac250,000\n\nAdjustments include:\n(i) Closing stocks: RM \u20ac28,300, WIP \u20ac27,600, FG \u20ac58,000\n(ii) Unrecorded credit sale of \u20ac10,800 (20% mark-up), goods still in stock\n(iii) Old machine sold for \u20ac7,000 (cost \u20ac30,000 on 01/09/2016) included in scrap sales\n(iv) P&M depreciation: 15% of cost, date of purchase to date of sale\n(v) Suspense: discount received \u20ac1,400 and credit purchases \u20ac11,000 errors\n(vi) 2% wage increase backdated 3 months from 01/10/2021\n(vii) Store built by employees - labour \u20ac60,000 + materials \u20ac62,000, not recorded\n(viii) Bank reconciliation discrepancies\n(ix) Provide for investment income, debenture interest, bad debts 4%, buildings depreciation 2%\n\nRequired:\n(a) Manufacturing, Trading and P&L account for year ended 31/12/2021 (75)\n(b) Balance sheet as at 31/12/2021 (45)\n(120 marks)", a:"KEY ANSWERS:\n\nManufacturing Account:\n- Purchases raw materials: \u20ac709,400 (760,400 + 11,000 - 62,000)\n- Factory wages: \u20ac88,440 (148,000 + 740 - 60,300)\n- General factory overheads: \u20ac114,300 (126,700 - 1,400 - 11,000)\n- Depreciation P&M: \u20ac47,625 (old machine 12,750 + remaining 34,875)\n- Loss on machine: \u20ac2,375 (30,000 - 7,000 - 20,625)\n- Depreciation buildings: \u20ac20,246 (2% x 1,012,300)\n- Cost of Manufacture: \u20ac1,047,886\n\nTrading & P&L:\n- Sales: \u20ac1,660,800 (1,650,000 + 10,800)\n- Closing stock FG: \u20ac49,000 (58,000 - 9,000 cost of goods sent)\n- Gross Profit: \u20ac623,514\n- Investment income: \u20ac7,500 (4% of 250,000 x 0.75)\n- Debenture interest: \u20ac23,000 (5,000 + 18,000 OR 3,000 + 20,000)\n- Net Profit: \u20ac524,452\n- P&L balance 31/12/2021: \u20ac566,452\n\nBalance Sheet:\n- Factory buildings cost: \u20ac1,012,300 (890,000 + 60,300 + 62,000)\n- P&M cost: \u20ac310,000 (340,000 - 30,000)\n- Bank (overdraft): \u20ac80,900\n- Debtors: \u20ac81,550 (76,350 + 10,800 - 5,000 - 600)\n- Investment income due: \u20ac4,700\n\nWhy: The store built by employees capitalises labour and materials to buildings. The wage increase of 2% for 3 months (148,000 x 2% x 3/12 = \u20ac740) affects both wages expense and wages due. The machine disposal requires calculating accumulated depreciation from 01/09/2016 to 31/03/2021."},
    {num:2, label:"Q1B: Company Final Accounts (McCormack Ltd)", q:"McCormack Ltd has authorised capital of \u20ac2,500,000 (1,500,000 ordinary shares + 1,000,000 4% preference shares at \u20ac1 each).\n\nTrial balance on 31/12/2021 includes:\n- Land and buildings (Land cost \u20ac1,000,000): \u20ac1,760,000\n- Office equipment (Cost \u20ac460,000): \u20ac357,000\n- Purchases and sales: \u20ac905,000 / \u20ac1,850,000\n- 6% Debentures (incl. \u20ac60,000 issued 01/06/2021): \u20ac360,000\n- 4% Investments 01/04/2021: \u20ac75,000\n\nAdjustments include:\n(i) Closing stock \u20ac82,800, includes sale-or-return goods (retail \u20ac9,250, 25% mark-up)\n(ii) Equipment depreciation: useful life 6 years, 4% residual scrap value\n(iii) Warehouse destroyed by fire, insurance \u20ac115,000 (cost \u20ac120,000)\n(iv) Buildings depreciated at 2% of cost\n(v) Bank reconciliation with multiple discrepancies\n(vi) Patents incorporating 4 months investment income, written off over 5 years from 2020\n(vii) Directors recommend: investment income due, debenture interest due, MD bonus 2% on sales over \u20ac1,500,000, bad debts 3%, transfer \u20ac250,000 to capital reserve, corporation tax \u20ac60,000\n\nRequired:\n(a) Trading and P&L for year ended 31/12/2021 (75)\n(b) Balance sheet as at 31/12/2021 (45)\n(120 marks)", a:"KEY ANSWERS:\n\nTrading & P&L:\n- Purchases: \u20ac875,600 (905,000 - 7,400 - 22,000)\n- Closing stock: \u20ac75,400 (82,800 - 7,400)\n- Gross Profit: \u20ac998,300\n- Bad debts written off: \u20ac10,500 (bankrupt debtor 4,500/0.30 x 0.70)\n- Increase in BDP: \u20ac134 (7,134 - 7,000)\n- Patents written off: \u20ac16,250 ((64,000 + 1,000)/4)\n- Depreciation equipment: \u20ac70,400 (440,000 x 96%/6)\n- Loss on disposal equipment: \u20ac400 (65,000 - 41,600 - 23,000)\n- Depreciation buildings: \u20ac12,800 ((1,640,000 - 1,000,000) x 2%)\n- Loss on fire: \u20ac5,000 (120,000 - 115,000)\n- Directors fees: \u20ac98,000 (91,000 + 7,000 bonus)\n- Bad debt recovered: \u20ac12,000 (9,000 + 3,000)\n- Investment income: \u20ac2,250 (75,000 x 0.04/12 x 9)\n- Debenture interest: \u20ac20,100 (18,000 + 2,100 OR 7,500 + 12,600)\n- Net Profit after tax: \u20ac474,366\n- P&L balance: \u20ac286,266\n\nBalance Sheet:\n- Equipment cost: \u20ac440,000 (460,000 - 65,000 + 45,000)\n- Acc dep equipment: \u20ac131,800 (103,000 + 70,400 - 41,600)\n- Bank (overdraft): \u20ac53,900\n- Directors fees due: \u20ac7,000\n\nWhy: Sale-or-return goods must be reversed from both purchases and stock. The MD bonus commission = 2% x (\u20ac1,850,000 - \u20ac1,500,000) = \u20ac7,000."},
    {num:3, label:"Q2: Cash Flow Statement (Puspure plc)", q:"Given the balance sheets of Puspure plc as at 31/12/2021 and 31/12/2020 together with an abridged P&L for year ended 31/12/2021.\n\nP&L: Operating Profit \u20ac227,000; Investment income \u20ac3,800; Interest (\u20ac12,000); Tax (\u20ac66,000); Dividends (\u20ac30,800); Retained profit \u20ac122,000.\n\nKey balance sheet changes:\n- Investments: \u20ac165,000 from \u20ac185,000\n- Buildings cost: \u20ac850,000 from \u20ac732,000 (no disposals)\n- Machinery cost: \u20ac397,000 from \u20ac438,000 (no purchases, disposal for \u20ac33,000)\n- Debentures: \u20ac100,000 from \u20ac200,000\n- Ordinary shares: \u20ac770,000 from \u20ac700,000\n- Share premium: \u20ac12,000 from nil\n\nAdditional info: Depreciation on machinery in operating profit = \u20ac30,400\n\nRequired:\n(a) Cash flow statement including reconciliation statements (52)\n(b) (i) What is a Financial Reporting Standard? (ii) Distinguish cash gain vs non-cash gain with examples (8)\n(60 marks)", a:"KEY ANSWERS:\n\nReconciliation of operating profit to net cash flow from operating activities:\n- Operating Profit: \u20ac227,000\n- Add: Depreciation charge: \u20ac45,400 (buildings 15,000 + machinery 30,400)\n- Less: Profit on sale of machinery: (\u20ac1,000) (33,000 - cost 41,000 + dep 9,000)\n- Less: Increase in stock: (\u20ac36,000)\n- Less: Increase in debtors: (\u20ac13,400)\n- Add: Increase in creditors: \u20ac9,000\n- Net cash inflow from operating activities: \u20ac231,000\n\nCash Flow Statement:\n- Operating activities: \u20ac231,000\n- Returns on investment: Investment income received \u20ac3,700, Debenture interest paid (\u20ac11,400) = (\u20ac7,700)\n- Taxation paid: (\u20ac62,000)\n- Capital expenditure: Buildings (\u20ac118,000), Sale of machinery \u20ac33,000, Sale of investments \u20ac20,000 = (\u20ac65,000)\n- Dividends paid: (\u20ac30,800)\n- Management of liquid resources: Government securities (\u20ac25,000)\n- Financing: Repayment debentures (\u20ac100,000), Issue shares \u20ac70,000, Share premium \u20ac12,000 = (\u20ac18,000)\n- Increase in cash: \u20ac22,500\n\nReconciliation of net cash to movement in net debt:\n- Increase in cash: \u20ac22,500\n- Purchase of liquid resources: \u20ac25,000\n- Repayment of debentures: \u20ac100,000\n- Change in net debt: \u20ac147,500\n\n(b)(i) A Financial Reporting Standard is a rule that must be applied to all financial statements to give a true and fair view. It sets out best practice allowing comparison year-to-year and company-to-company.\n\n(b)(ii) Cash gain: increases profit AND cash (e.g., investment income \u20ac3,700). Non-cash gain: increases profits but NOT cash (e.g., profit on sale of fixed asset \u20ac1,000).\n\nWhy: Depreciation is added back because it reduces profit but involves no cash outflow. Profit on disposal is removed because sale proceeds are shown separately under capital expenditure."},
    {num:4, label:"Q3: Correction of Errors and Suspense Account (Fletcher Ltd)", q:"The trial balance of Fletcher Ltd, a sports clothing retailer, failed to agree on 31/12/2021. The difference was entered in a suspense account.\n\nErrors discovered:\n(i) Credit purchases \u20ac2,400 from E Hegarty entered as \u20ac2,040 in day books, then posted on incorrect side of Hegarty's account as \u20ac4,020\n(ii) Private debt \u20ac750 owed by Fletcher offset against business debt \u20ac800 owed to Fletcher Ltd. No entries made.\n(iii) Payment of \u20ac1,000 from F Murtagh (former debtor, debt previously written off, 80% of original). Only entry: full amount written off credited to debtors.\n(iv) Credit note sent to K Mullan for \u20ac240 misread as credit note received from A Keogh\n(v) Equipment sold (cost \u20ac8,400, BV \u20ac3,360) for \u20ac3,300 cash. Entered as \u20ac3,630 debit to sales, credit to debtor's account.\n\nRequired:\n(a) Journalise the necessary corrections (40)\n(b) Statement of corrected net profit (original \u20ac27,900) (12)\n(c) (i) Purpose of trial balance (ii) Types of errors affecting trial balance (8)\n(60 marks)", a:"KEY ANSWERS:\n\n(a) Journal Entries:\n(i) Dr Purchases \u20ac360, Dr Suspense \u20ac6,060, Cr Creditors \u20ac6,420\n(ii) Dr Drawings \u20ac750, Cr Debtors \u20ac800, Dr Discount Allowed \u20ac50\n(iii) Dr Debtors \u20ac1,250, Cr Suspense \u20ac1,250; Dr Bank \u20ac1,000, Dr Debtors \u20ac250, Cr Bad Debt Recovered \u20ac1,250\n(iv) Dr Purchases Returns \u20ac240, Cr Creditors/Keogh \u20ac240; Dr Sales Returns \u20ac240, Cr Debtors/Mullan \u20ac240\n(v) Cr Sales \u20ac3,630, Dr Debtors \u20ac3,630; Cr Equipment \u20ac8,400, Dr Prov for Dep \u20ac5,040, Dr Cash \u20ac3,300, Dr Loss on Disposal \u20ac60\n\n(b) Corrected Net Profit:\n- Original: \u20ac27,900\n- Add: Bad debt recovered \u20ac1,250, Sales reversed \u20ac3,630 = \u20ac4,880\n- Less: Purchases \u20ac360, Purchases returns \u20ac240, Discount \u20ac50, Sales returns \u20ac240, Loss on sale \u20ac60 = (\u20ac950)\n- Corrected Net Profit: \u20ac31,830\n\n(c)(i) A trial balance checks the accuracy of double entry bookkeeping before preparing final accounts. Debits should equal credits.\n(c)(ii) Errors affecting the trial balance:\n1. Entering one figure on one side but a different figure on the other side\n2. Entering a figure on one side but on the same side of another account\n3. Entering a figure on one side but nothing on the other\n4. Mathematical/calculation errors in totalling or closing off\n\nWhy: In (i), the suspense entry of \u20ac6,060 arises because: the correct credit to Hegarty should be \u20ac2,400, but it was posted as \u20ac4,020 debit (a swing of \u20ac6,420), while purchases were understated by \u20ac360."},
    {num:5, label:"Q4: Revaluation of Fixed Assets (Ryan Ltd)", q:"On 1 January 2007, Ryan Ltd purchased new property for \u20ac900,000 (land \u20ac150,000, buildings \u20ac750,000). Buildings depreciated at 2% straight-line. Full year's depreciation in year of acquisition, none in year of disposal.\n\nKey events:\n- 01/01/2017: Revalued at \u20ac1,080,000 (land \u20ac210,000)\n- 01/01/2018: Purchased building \u20ac250,000. Also \u20ac90,000 paid for repairs and \u20ac30,000 for extension.\n- 01/01/2019: Sold land for \u20ac235,000 (revalued at \u20ac210,000)\n- 01/01/2020: Revalued remaining property at \u20ac1,426,000\n- 01/01/2021: Building sold for \u20ac980,000, new building purchased for \u20ac475,000\n\nRequired: Show the Land and Building Account, Provision for Depreciation Account, Revaluation Reserve Account, and Disposal Accounts for each year 2017-2021.\n(60 marks)", a:"KEY ANSWERS:\n\nLand and Building Account:\n- 01/01/2017: Balance \u20ac900,000, Revaluation Reserve \u20ac180,000 -> Balance \u20ac1,080,000\n- 01/01/2018: Add purchases \u20ac250,000 + \u20ac90,000 + \u20ac30,000 -> Balance \u20ac1,450,000\n- 01/01/2019: Disposal \u20ac210,000 -> Balance \u20ac1,240,000\n- 01/01/2020: Revaluation Reserve \u20ac186,000 -> Balance \u20ac1,426,000\n- 01/01/2021: Disposal \u20ac1,000,500, Revaluation Reserve \u20ac49,500 -> Balance \u20ac475,000\n\nProvision for Depreciation:\n- 01/01/2017: Balance \u20ac150,000 (2% x 750,000 x 10 years), transferred to Revaluation Reserve\n- 31/12/2017: Charge \u20ac17,400 (2% x 870,000)\n- 31/12/2018: Charge \u20ac24,800 (2% x 1,240,000)\n- 31/12/2019: Charge \u20ac24,800\n- 01/01/2020: Balance \u20ac67,000 transferred to Revaluation Reserve\n- 31/12/2020: Charge \u20ac28,520 (2% x 1,426,000)\n- 01/01/2021: On disposal \u20ac20,010, Revaluation Reserve \u20ac8,510\n- 31/12/2021: Charge \u20ac9,500 (2% x 475,000)\n\nDisposal of Land 2019: Land \u20ac210,000, Bank \u20ac235,000, Profit \u20ac25,000\nDisposal of Building 2021: Building \u20ac1,000,500, Depreciation \u20ac20,010, Bank \u20ac980,000, Loss \u20ac490\n\nWhy: When assets are revalued, accumulated depreciation is transferred to the revaluation reserve. Future depreciation is based on the revalued amount. When a revalued asset is sold, any remaining revaluation surplus is also dealt with."},
    {num:6, label:"Q5: Published Accounts or Interpretation", q:"Section 2 question. Candidates answer one of Q5, Q6, or Q7.\n\nTypical topics in this section include:\n- Published Final Accounts (Companies Act format)\n- Interpretation of Accounts (ratio analysis)\n- Service Firm / Club Accounts\n\nThese questions carry 100 marks each and test the ability to present accounts in the proper published format or analyse financial performance using ratios.\n(100 marks)", a:"Section 2 questions for 2022 covered topics including published accounts, interpretation of financial statements, and analysis of company performance.\n\nKey ratios students should know:\n- Return on Capital Employed (ROCE) = (Net Profit + Interest) / Capital Employed x 100\n- Earnings Per Share (EPS) = (Net Profit - Pref Dividend) / No. of Ordinary Shares\n- Price/Earnings Ratio = Market Price / EPS\n- Dividend Cover = (Net Profit - Pref Dividend) / Ordinary Dividend\n- Dividend Yield = DPS / Market Price x 100\n- Acid Test Ratio = (Current Assets - Stock) / Current Liabilities\n\nWhy: These ratios allow stakeholders to assess profitability, dividend policy, liquidity, and investment potential of a company."},
    {num:7, label:"Q8/Q9: Management Accounting", q:"Section 3 question. Candidates answer one of Q8 or Q9.\n\nTypical topics include:\n- Marginal Costing and Break-Even Analysis\n- Budgeting (Cash Budgets, Production Budgets)\n- Absorption Costing\n- Product Costing\n\nEach question carries 80 marks.\n(80 marks)", a:"Management accounting questions require students to apply costing and budgeting techniques.\n\nKey concepts:\n- Break-even point = Fixed Costs / Contribution per unit\n- Contribution = Selling Price - Variable Cost\n- Margin of Safety = Actual Sales - Break-even Sales\n- Cash Budget: Opening balance + Receipts - Payments = Closing balance\n- Absorption costing allocates fixed overheads to products\n- Marginal costing treats fixed costs as period costs\n\nWhy: Management accounting helps internal decision-making by providing cost analysis, budgets, and break-even analysis that guide pricing, production, and investment decisions."}
  ],
  "2023": [
    {num:1, label:"Q1A: Sole Trader Final Accounts (V. Leahy)", q:"Trial balance of V. Leahy on 31/12/2022 includes:\n- Patents (incorporating 2 months investment income): \u20ac48,800\n- Land and buildings: \u20ac850,000 (acc dep \u20ac105,000)\n- Delivery vans: \u20ac480,000 (acc dep \u20ac70,000)\n- Equipment at cost: \u20ac153,500\n- 4% Investments acquired 01/07/2022: \u20ac180,000\n- Stock 01/01/2022: \u20ac70,700\n- Sales: \u20ac1,848,900\n- Purchases: \u20ac1,193,500\n- 3% Fixed mortgage (incl. \u20ac50,000 issued 01/06/2022): \u20ac320,000\n- Capital: \u20ac762,000\n\nAdjustments:\n(i) Closing stock \u20ac82,600 includes damaged stock (cost \u20ac5,800, NRV 75% of cost)\n(ii) Goods in transit \u20ac15,375 including VAT at 23% - not recorded\n(iii) Depreciation on vans 20% of cost. Van traded in: cost \u20ac35,000 (30/06/2018), allowance \u20ac3,000 against new van \u20ac80,000. Net amount entered as purchase of trading stock.\n(iv) Suspense: incorrect mortgage interest figure + discount received \u20ac600 entered only in discount account\n(v) Patents written off over 10 years from 2020\n(vi) Goods taken by Leahy for personal use (retail \u20ac3,600 = cost + 20%)\n(vii) Land and buildings revalued at \u20ac950,000 on 01/01/2022 (land \u20ac200,000). Buildings depreciated at 2% of cost.\n(viii) Bank reconciliation discrepancies\n(ix) Provide for investment income, mortgage interest (20% private), bad debts 6%, equipment dep 10%\n\nRequired:\n(a) Trading and P&L for year ended 31/12/2022 (75)\n(b) Balance sheet as at 31/12/2022 (45)\n(120 marks)", a:"KEY ANSWERS:\n\nTrading & P&L:\n- Sales: \u20ac1,848,900\n- Purchases: \u20ac1,126,000 (1,193,500 + 12,500 - 77,000 - 3,000)\n- Closing stock: \u20ac93,650 (82,600 - 1,450 + 12,500)\n- Gross Profit: \u20ac745,850\n- Loss on sale of van: \u20ac2,250 (35,000 - 3,000 - 29,750)\n- Depreciation vans: \u20ac98,250 (72,000 + 26,250 OR 5,250 + 89,000 + 4,000)\n- Increase in BDP: \u20ac1,974 (4,074 - 2,100)\n- Depreciation buildings: \u20ac15,000 (750,000 x 2%)\n- Salaries & general expenses: \u20ac135,400 (136,400 - 600 - 400)\n- Patent written off: \u20ac6,250 ((48,800 + 1,200)/8)\n- Depreciation equipment: \u20ac15,350 (153,500 x 10%)\n- Bad debt recovered: \u20ac1,700\n- Investment income: \u20ac3,600 (180,000 x 4% x 6/12)\n- Mortgage interest: \u20ac7,180 (8,100 + 875 - 1,795 OR 3,375 + 5,600 - 1,795)\n- Net Profit: \u20ac418,396\n\nBalance Sheet:\n- Patent: \u20ac43,750 (50,000 - 6,250)\n- Land & buildings: \u20ac950,000, Acc dep \u20ac15,000, NBV \u20ac935,000\n- Delivery vans cost: \u20ac525,000 (480,000 + 80,000 - 35,000)\n- Vans acc dep: \u20ac138,500 (70,000 + 98,250 - 29,750)\n- Debtors: \u20ac67,900, BDP: \u20ac4,074 (67,900 x 6%)\n- Creditors: \u20ac113,375 (98,600 + 15,375 - 600)\n- Bank (overdraft): \u20ac52,100 (53,600 - 1,500 OR 50,300 + 1,800)\n- Revaluation reserve: \u20ac205,000 (100,000 + 105,000)\n- Drawings: \u20ac49,795 (45,000 + 1,795 + 3,000)\n\nWhy: The damaged stock adjustment reduces stock by \u20ac1,450 (5,800 - 75% x 5,800). Goods in transit add to both purchases and creditors at VAT-exclusive amount (\u20ac12,500). The van trade-in was wrongly treated as a purchase, so \u20ac77,000 must be reversed from purchases. Mortgage interest: 20% is private so added to drawings."},
    {num:2, label:"Q1B: Company Final Accounts (East Elm Ltd)", q:"East Elm Ltd has authorised capital of \u20ac1,400,000 (900,000 ordinary + 500,000 4% preference at \u20ac1 each).\n\nTrial balance on 31/12/2022 includes:\n- Land and buildings at cost: \u20ac950,000 (acc dep \u20ac120,000)\n- Office equipment (cost \u20ac65,000): \u20ac32,000\n- Delivery vans (cost \u20ac175,000): \u20ac135,000\n- Patent (incorporating 5 months investment income): \u20ac53,300\n- 3% Investments acquired 01/02/2022: \u20ac124,000\n- 6% Debentures (incl. \u20ac60,000 issued 01/06/2022): \u20ac280,000\n- Purchases and sales: \u20ac758,000 / \u20ac1,150,000\n\nAdjustments:\n(i) Closing stock \u20ac95,200 includes damaged stock (cost \u20ac7,200, NRV 25% of cost)\n(ii) Patents written off over 6 years from 2021\n(iii) Goods in transit \u20ac19,680 incl. VAT 23% - not recorded\n(iv) Goods returned to supplier (\u20ac12,000 retail = cost + 25%), restocking charge 10% of cost\n(v) Depreciation on vans 15% of cost. Van traded in (cost \u20ac36,000 on 30/06/2019, allowance \u20ac18,000 against new van \u20ac45,000) treated as purchase of trading stock\n(vi) Suspense: incorrect debenture interest + PAYE \u20ac4,500 on wrong side\n(vii) Land and buildings revalued at \u20ac1,100,000 on 01/01/2022 (land \u20ac300,000). Buildings dep at 2%.\n(viii) Bank reconciliation: bankrupt debtor payment \u20ac900 (30c in \u20ac1), director cheque \u20ac1,300 not presented\n(ix) Directors recommend: investment income due, debenture interest due, equipment dep 10% reducing balance, BDP 6%, corporation tax \u20ac35,000\n\nRequired:\n(a) Trading and P&L for year ended 31/12/2022 (75)\n(b) Balance sheet as at 31/12/2022 (45)\n(120 marks)", a:"KEY ANSWERS:\n\nTrading & P&L:\n- Purchases: \u20ac747,960 (758,000 + 16,000 + 960 - 27,000)\n- Closing stock: \u20ac105,800 (95,200 - 5,400 + 16,000)\n- Gross Profit: \u20ac452,440\n- Bad debts written off: \u20ac2,100 (900/0.3 = 3,000 - 900)\n- Loss on sale of van: \u20ac2,700 (36,000 - 18,000 - 15,300)\n- Depreciation vans: \u20ac27,150 (8,750 + 18,400 OR 1,800 + 20,850 + 4,500)\n- Patents written off: \u20ac10,970 ((53,300 + 1,550)/5)\n- Depreciation equipment: \u20ac3,200 (32,000 x 10%)\n- Salaries & general expenses: \u20ac225,400 (232,400 + 2,000 - 9,000)\n- Depreciation buildings: \u20ac16,000 ((1,100,000 - 300,000) x 2%)\n- Decrease in BDP: \u20ac842 (6,200 - 5,358)\n- Investment income: \u20ac3,410 (124,000 x 0.03/12 x 11)\n- Debenture interest: \u20ac15,300 (5,500 + 9,800 OR 13,200 + 2,100)\n- Net Profit after tax: \u20ac111,972\n- P&L balance: \u20ac7,972\n\nBalance Sheet:\n- Patents: \u20ac43,880 (54,850 - 10,970)\n- Delivery vans cost: \u20ac184,000 (175,000 + 45,000 - 36,000)\n- Acc dep vans: \u20ac51,850 (40,000 + 27,150 - 15,300)\n- Debtors: \u20ac89,300 (92,300 - 3,000)\n- Creditors: \u20ac85,840 (65,200 + 19,680 + 960)\n- Bank (overdraft): \u20ac32,500 (33,400 - 900 OR 31,200 + 1,300)\n- PAYE & PRSI: \u20ac39,200 (48,200 - 9,000)\n- Revaluation Reserve: \u20ac270,000 (150,000 + 120,000)\n\nWhy: Damaged stock reduces to NRV: 7,200 x 25% = 1,800, so deduction = 5,400. The restocking charge of 10% of cost price (10% x \u20ac9,600 = \u20ac960) increases purchases. Equipment uses reducing balance depreciation, so 10% of NBV \u20ac32,000."},
    {num:3, label:"Q2: Incomplete Records (P. Shepard)", q:"On 01/01/2022, P. Shepard purchased a business with:\nBuildings \u20ac300,000; stock \u20ac63,000; debtors \u20ac73,200; equipment \u20ac70,000; wages due \u20ac1,700; trade creditors \u20ac57,700; rates prepaid \u20ac450; delivery van \u20ac35,000; cash \u20ac300.\n\nCash payments: Lodgements \u20ac196,000; general expenses \u20ac12,500; purchases \u20ac84,000\nBank payments: Interest \u20ac3,300; creditors \u20ac37,000; rates \u20ac6,000; general expenses \u20ac81,000; equipment (01/05/2022) \u20ac24,000; light and heat \u20ac20,700\nBank lodgements: Debtors \u20ac46,000; cash \u20ac196,000\n\nWeekly: Goods from stock \u20ac120 and cash \u20ac180 for household expenses.\nBorrowed \u20ac150,000 on 01/08/2022 for building, interest 7% p.a.\nGeneral expenses includes diesel \u20ac4,100 (20% private use). 15% of light/heat and 20% of interest = private.\n\nClosing: stock \u20ac40,700 (incl. heating oil \u20ac500); electricity due \u20ac700; debtors \u20ac43,000; creditors \u20ac55,400; cash \u20ac430; wages due \u20ac1,400.\n\nDepreciation: equipment 10% of cost, buildings 2% of cost, vans 20% of cost. BDP: 4% of debtors.\n\nRequired:\n(a) Trading and P&L for year ended 31/12/2022 (52)\n(b)(i) What additional information from double entry? (ii) Advice on record keeping (8)\n(60 marks)", a:"KEY ANSWERS:\n\nTrading & P&L:\n- Sales: \u20ac317,790\n  Credit: 46,000 + 43,000 - 73,200 = 15,800\n  Cash: 196,000 + 12,500 + 84,000 + 9,360 + 430 - 300 = 301,990\n- Purchases: \u20ac112,460\n  Credit: 37,000 + 55,400 - 57,700 = 34,700\n  Cash: 84,000\n  Less drawings of stock: (6,240) [120 x 52]\n- Closing stock: \u20ac40,200 (40,700 - 500 heating oil)\n- Gross Profit: \u20ac182,530\n- General expenses: \u20ac92,380 (12,500 + 81,000 + 1,400 - 1,700 - 820)\n- Light and heat: \u20ac17,765 (20,700 - 500 + 700 - 3,135)\n- Rates: \u20ac5,950 (6,000 + 450 - 500)\n- Increase in BDP: \u20ac1,720 (43,000 x 4%)\n- Depreciation: equipment \u20ac8,600, premises \u20ac7,250, vehicles \u20ac7,000\n- Interest: \u20ac3,500 (4,375 - 875 private)\n- Net Profit: \u20ac38,515\n\n(b)(i) Double entry would provide: General/Nominal Ledger, Trial Balance, Total Sales and Purchases figures, Bank balance, Capital/Drawings details, detailed expense and income breakdowns.\n(b)(ii) Shepard should keep a detailed cash book and general ledger supported by appropriate subsidiary day books. This would enable preparation of accurate final accounts without reliance on rough estimates.\n\nWhy: In incomplete records, sales and purchases must be reconstructed from cash/bank records and opening/closing debtors/creditors. Private use portions (diesel 20%, light/heat 15%, interest 20%) are excluded from business expenses and treated as drawings."},
    {num:4, label:"Q3: Creditors Control Account (T. Gallagher)", q:"The creditors ledger control account of T. Gallagher showed balances: \u20ac48,760 cr and \u20ac280 dr on 31/12/2022. These did not agree with the schedule of creditors.\n\nErrors found:\n(i) Purchases of \u20ac9,570 entered on debit side of supplier (includes cash purchases \u20ac2,300)\n(ii) Invoice for \u20ac730 entered in day book as \u20ac370, no entry in supplier's account\n(iii) Discount disallowed \u20ac94 recorded as discount received \u20ac90 in general ledger, debited as \u20ac9 in supplier's account\n(iv) Goods returned \u20ac650, credit note showed 10% restocking charge, total credited to creditor's account\n(v) Credit note for \u20ac580, only entry was \u20ac58 credited to supplier\n(vi) Customer who is also supplier, debt of \u20ac420 offset, entered as \u20ac240 on correct side of supplier\n\nRequired:\n(a) Adjusted creditors ledger control account (24)\n(b) Adjusted schedule of creditors (28)\n(c)(i) Why are creditors control accounts prepared? (ii) Explain restocking charge (8)\n(60 marks)", a:"KEY ANSWERS:\n\n(a) Adjusted Creditors Control Account:\nDebit side: Balance b/d \u20ac280, Credit note (v) \u20ac580, Contra/Debtors (vi) \u20ac420, Balance c/d \u20ac48,369\nCredit side: Balance b/d \u20ac48,760, Purchases (ii) \u20ac360, Discount disallowed (iii) \u20ac184, Restocking charge (iv) \u20ac65, Balance c/d \u20ac280\nTotals: \u20ac49,649\n\n(b) Schedule of Creditors:\n- Balance as per list: \u20ac30,584\n- Add: Purchases (i) \u20ac16,840, Purchases (ii) \u20ac730, Discount disallowed (iii) \u20ac103, Restocking (iv) \u20ac650 = \u20ac18,323\n- Deduct: Credit note (v) \u20ac638, Contra (vi) \u20ac180 = (\u20ac818)\n- Net balance: \u20ac48,089\n\n(c)(i) Why creditors control accounts are prepared:\n1. Check accuracy of ledgers by comparing control balance with schedule total\n2. Locate errors quickly, narrow search to confined areas\n3. Useful for finding credit purchases from incomplete records\n4. Allow amounts owed to creditors to be found quickly\n\n(c)(ii) A restocking charge is a fee charged when stock is returned to cover the cost of repackaging goods or when goods have been damaged on customer's premises.\n\nWhy: The control account is adjusted for errors that affect the general ledger (purchases omission, discount correction). The schedule is adjusted for errors in individual creditor accounts (wrong side posting, omitted entries). Both should agree after corrections."},
    {num:5, label:"Q4: Tabular Statement", q:"A tabular statement question requiring students to record a series of transactions affecting balance sheet items in columnar format.\n\nTransactions typically involve:\n- Purchase/sale of assets\n- Share issues at premium\n- Revaluations\n- Goodwill\n- Bad debt provisions\n- Depreciation\n- Accruals and prepayments\n\nStudents must show the effect of each transaction on the relevant balance sheet categories.\n(60 marks)", a:"KEY APPROACH:\n\nIn a tabular statement:\n- Each transaction is shown on a separate row\n- Columns represent balance sheet items (Fixed Assets, Stock, Debtors, Bank, Creditors, Share Capital, Reserves, P&L)\n- Each row must balance (total assets = total liabilities)\n- Opening balances are shown first, then each adjustment\n\nFor the 2023 Q4, key transactions included:\n- Asset purchases and revaluations\n- Share issues at premium\n- Goodwill calculations\n- BDP adjustments\n- Depreciation charges\n- Rates prepaid adjustments\n\nWhy: Tabular statements test understanding of how individual transactions affect the balance sheet. Each transaction must maintain the accounting equation: Assets = Liabilities + Capital."},
    {num:6, label:"Q5: Interpretation of Accounts", q:"Interpretation of Accounts question requiring calculation of financial ratios and analysis of company performance.\n\nTypical ratios to calculate:\n(i) Opening stock or cash purchases from given data\n(ii) Return on Capital Employed (ROCE)\n(iii) Price/Earnings Ratio\n(iv) Dividend Cover\n(v) Dividend Yield\n\nPart (b) asks students to comment on performance, state of affairs, and dividend policy using relevant ratios.\n(100 marks)", a:"KEY ANSWERS (2023 Q5 - O'Malley PLC):\n\n(i) Rate of Stock Turnover = Cost of Sales / Average Stock = 14 times\n    Average Stock = \u20ac560,000/14 = \u20ac40,000\n    Opening Stock = (\u20ac40,000 x 2) - \u20ac42,000 = \u20ac38,000\n\n(ii) ROCE = (Net Profit + Interest) / Capital Employed x 100\n    = (\u20ac104,000 + \u20ac32,000) / \u20ac1,028,000 x 100 = 13.23%\n\n(iii) Price/Earnings Ratio = Market Price / EPS\n    EPS = (\u20ac104,000 - \u20ac4,000) / 450,000 = 22.22 cent\n    P/E = 130c / 22.22c = 5.85 years\n\n(iv) Dividend Cover = (Net Profit - Pref Dividend) / Ordinary Dividend\n    = (\u20ac104,000 - \u20ac4,000) / \u20ac36,000 = 2.78 times\n\n(v) Dividend Yield = DPS / Market Price x 100\n    DPS = \u20ac36,000 / 450,000 = 8 cent\n    = 8c / 130c x 100 = 6.15%\n\nPerformance Analysis:\n- ROCE of 13.23% has decreased from 14.28% but is still well above risk-free returns (0-2%) and the 8% paid to debenture holders\n- EPS has slightly decreased from 23c to 22.22c\n- Dividend Cover improved from 2.57 to 2.78 times, meaning more profit is being retained\n- The company is a liquid company with acid test ratio of 1.2:1\n\nWhy: These ratios allow shareholders, creditors, and investors to assess whether the company is profitable, well-managed, and a good investment."},
    {num:7, label:"Q8/Q9: Management Accounting", q:"Section 3 question. Candidates answer one of Q8 or Q9.\n\nTypical 2023 topics include:\n- Marginal Costing and Break-Even Analysis\n- Budgeting and Cash Budgets\n- Absorption Costing vs Marginal Costing\n- Make or Buy decisions\n\nEach question carries 80 marks.\n(80 marks)", a:"Management accounting questions require application of costing techniques to business decisions.\n\nKey formulas:\n- Break-even point (units) = Fixed Costs / Contribution per unit\n- Break-even point (\u20ac) = Fixed Costs / C/S Ratio\n- Contribution/Sales Ratio = Contribution / Sales x 100\n- Margin of Safety = Actual Sales - Break-even Sales\n- Target Profit: Units = (Fixed Costs + Target Profit) / Contribution per unit\n\nAbsorption vs Marginal:\n- Absorption: allocates all overheads (fixed + variable) to products\n- Marginal: only variable costs charged to products; fixed costs = period costs\n- Difference in profit = change in stock x fixed overhead per unit\n\nWhy: Management accounting supports internal decision-making. Break-even analysis helps determine minimum sales needed. Marginal costing is useful for short-term decisions like special orders."}
  ],
  "2024": [
    {num:1, label:"Q1A: Company Final Accounts (Yeats Ltd)", q:"Yeats Ltd has authorised capital of \u20ac1,600,000 (1,000,000 ordinary + 600,000 4% preference at \u20ac1 each).\n\nTrial balance on 31/12/2023 includes:\n- Land and buildings at cost: \u20ac580,000 (acc dep buildings \u20ac38,000)\n- Delivery vans (cost \u20ac115,000): \u20ac80,000\n- 3% Investments acquired 01/05/2023: \u20ac120,000\n- Patents (incorporating 3 months investment income): \u20ac40,600\n- Purchases and sales: \u20ac747,000 / \u20ac1,080,700\n- 8% Debentures (incl. \u20ac40,000 issued 01/10/2023): \u20ac140,000\n- Salaries and general expenses (including suspense): \u20ac218,355\n\nAdjustments:\n(i) Closing stock \u20ac56,900 includes damaged stock (cost \u20ac3,800, NRV 60% of cost)\n(ii) Delivery vans: straight-line over 5 years, 5% scrap value. Van traded in (cost \u20ac40,000 in 2019) for \u20ac10,000 against new van \u20ac56,000 - entered as purchase of trading stock\n(iii) Sale-or-return goods entered as credit purchase (selling price \u20ac5,000 = cost + 25%)\n(iv) Patents written off over 7 years from 2021\n(v) Suspense: incorrect debenture interest + discount allowed \u20ac400 entered only in discount account\n(vi) New warehouse \u20ac100,000 + VAT 13.5% - total entered in land & buildings, no VAT entry\n(vii) Buildings dep at 2% (land cost \u20ac200,000). Revalued at \u20ac700,000 on 31/12/2023.\n(viii) Rent received for warehouse at \u20ac1,500/month from 01/06/2023\n(ix) Provide for investment income, debenture interest, BDP 4%, transfer \u20ac20,000 to capital reserve\n\nRequired:\n(a) Trading and P&L for year ended 31/12/2023 (75)\n(b) Balance sheet as at 31/12/2023 (45)\n(120 marks)", a:"KEY ANSWERS:\n\nTrading & P&L:\n- Purchases: \u20ac697,000 (747,000 - 46,000 - 4,000)\n- Closing stock: \u20ac51,380 (56,900 - 1,520 - 4,000)\n- Gross Profit: \u20ac390,680\n- Discount: \u20ac3,500\n- Depreciation vans: \u20ac24,890 (131,000 x 0.95/5)\n- Advertising: \u20ac25,145\n- Patents written off: \u20ac8,300 ((40,600 + 900)/5)\n- Depreciation buildings: \u20ac7,330 ((580,000 - 13,500 - 200,000) x 2%)\n- Salaries & general expenses: \u20ac218,155 (218,355 + 400 - 600)\n- Rent received: \u20ac10,500 (1,500 x 7 months)\n- Decrease in BDP: \u20ac432 (3,200 - 2,768)\n- Profit on disposal: \u20ac400 (40,000 - 30,400 - 10,000 + 400 profit)\n- Investment income: \u20ac2,400 (120,000 x 3% x 8/12)\n- Debenture interest: \u20ac8,800 (6,000 + 2,800 OR 8,000 + 800)\n- Net Profit: \u20ac108,292\n- Transfer to capital reserve: (\u20ac20,000)\n- P&L balance: \u20ac108,092\n\nBalance Sheet:\n- Patents: \u20ac33,200 (41,500 - 8,300)\n- Land & Buildings: \u20ac700,000 (revalued, no separate cost/dep)\n- Motor vehicles cost: \u20ac131,000 (115,000 + 56,000 - 40,000)\n- Motor vehicles acc dep: \u20ac29,490 (35,000 + 24,890 - 30,400)\n- Debtors: \u20ac69,200 (69,600 - 400)\n- BDP: \u20ac2,768 (69,200 x 4%)\n- VAT: \u20ac11,600 ((1,900) + 13,500)\n- Creditors: \u20ac60,900 (64,900 - 4,000)\n- Debenture interest due: \u20ac2,800\n- Rent receivable prepaid: \u20ac3,000\n- Revaluation reserve: \u20ac178,830 (133,500 + 38,000 + 7,330)\n- Capital reserve: \u20ac35,000 (15,000 + 20,000)\n\nWhy: The damaged stock reduces by \u20ac1,520 (3,800 - 60% x 3,800). Sale-or-return goods: cost = 5,000/1.25 = \u20ac4,000, reversed from both purchases and closing stock. The warehouse VAT (\u20ac13,500) was included in buildings cost but should be in VAT account. Van depreciation uses straight-line: (cost - 5% scrap) / 5 years."},
    {num:2, label:"Q1B: Company Final Accounts - Manufacturing (Sexton Ltd)", q:"Sexton Ltd has authorised capital of \u20ac1,500,000 (1,100,000 ordinary + 400,000 4% preference at \u20ac1 each).\n\nTrial balance on 31/12/2023 includes:\n- Factory land & buildings (cost \u20ac900,000): \u20ac812,000\n- Plant and machinery (cost \u20ac780,000): \u20ac680,000\n- Patents: \u20ac80,000\n- Stocks: RM \u20ac97,500, WIP \u20ac13,000, FG \u20ac76,000\n- Purchase of raw materials: \u20ac580,000\n- Sales: \u20ac1,692,100\n- Direct factory wages: \u20ac310,000\n- 8% Debentures: \u20ac200,000\n- 3% Investments acquired 01/08/2023: \u20ac150,000\n\nAdjustments:\n(i) Closing stocks: RM \u20ac33,400, WIP \u20ac22,100, FG \u20ac72,000\n(ii) Raw materials destroyed by fire (\u20ac5,800), insurance covers 90%\n(iii) Goods sent to customer on sale-or-return basis recorded as credit sale of \u20ac21,250 (25% mark-up)\n(iv) Suspense: discount allowed \u20ac800 in debtors only, credit purchase \u20ac3,000 on wrong side of creditor\n(v) Patents written off over 7 years from 2021\n(vi) Old machine sold for \u20ac7,000 (cost \u20ac40,000 on 30/09/2019). P&M dep at 15% of cost.\n(vii) Buildings dep at 2% (land cost \u20ac100,000). 80% factory, 20% admin. Revalue at \u20ac1,200,000 on 31/12/2023.\n(viii) Bank reconciliation: rent received \u20ac6,000, cheque \u20ac3,200 not presented, dishonoured cheque \u20ac1,800\n(ix) Provide for investment income, debenture interest, BDP 6%, transfer \u20ac20,000 to capital reserve\n\nRequired:\n(a) Manufacturing, Trading and P&L for year ended 31/12/2023 (75)\n(b) Balance sheet as at 31/12/2023 (45)\n(120 marks)", a:"KEY ANSWERS:\n\nManufacturing Account:\n- Purchases RM: \u20ac574,200 (580,000 - 5,800)\n- Carriage in: \u20ac15,800\n- Cost of RM consumed: \u20ac654,100\n- Factory wages: \u20ac310,000\n- Prime Cost: \u20ac964,100\n- Patent written off: \u20ac16,000 (80,000/5)\n- General factory overheads: \u20ac115,900 (110,700 + 6,000 - 800)\n- Depreciation P&M: \u20ac112,500 (29,250 + 29,250 OR 111,000 + 1,500)\n- Loss on machine: \u20ac12,000 (40,000 - 7,000 - 21,000)\n- Loss on damaged stock: \u20ac580 (5,800 - 5,220)\n- Depreciation factory buildings: \u20ac12,800 (2% x 800,000 x 80%)\n- Sale of scrap: (\u20ac4,200) (11,200 - 7,000)\n- Cost of Manufacture: \u20ac1,220,580\n\nTrading & P&L:\n- Sales: \u20ac1,670,850 (1,692,100 - 21,250)\n- Closing stock FG: \u20ac89,000 (72,000 + 17,000 cost of sale-or-return goods)\n- Gross Profit: \u20ac463,270\n- Discount: \u20ac800\n- Increase in BDP: \u20ac1,533 (25,550 x 6%)\n- Depreciation admin buildings: \u20ac3,200 (2% x 800,000 x 20%)\n- Rent: \u20ac3,000 (6,000 x 2/4 months)\n- Investment income: \u20ac1,875 (150,000 x 3% x 5/12)\n- Debenture interest: \u20ac16,000 (200,000 x 8%)\n- Net Profit: \u20ac234,612\n- P&L balance: \u20ac173,912\n\nBalance Sheet:\n- Patent: \u20ac64,000 (80,000 - 16,000)\n- Factory land & buildings: \u20ac1,300,000 (revalued)\n- P&M cost: \u20ac740,000 (780,000 - 40,000)\n- P&M acc dep: \u20ac191,500 (100,000 + 112,500 - 21,000)\n- Debtors: \u20ac25,550 (45,000 - 21,250 + 1,800)\n- Compensation due: \u20ac5,220 (5,800 x 90%)\n- Bank (overdraft): \u20ac3,800 (8,000 + 1,800 - 6,000 OR 600 + 3,200)\n- Creditors: \u20ac58,000 (52,000 + 6,000)\n- Revaluation reserve: \u20ac504,000 (400,000 + 88,000 + 16,000)\n\nWhy: The sale-or-return goods must be reversed: deduct \u20ac21,250 from sales, add cost \u20ac17,000 (21,250/1.25) back to closing stock FG. Machine accumulated dep = 15% x 40,000 x 3.5 years (30/09/2019 to 31/03/2023) = \u20ac21,000. Rent only 2 months earned out of 4 months received."},
    {num:3, label:"Q2: Published Accounts (Lyne plc)", q:"Lyne plc has authorised share capital of \u20ac850,000 (650,000 ordinary + 200,000 4% preference at \u20ac1 each).\n\nTrial balance on 31/12/2023 includes:\n- Land & buildings at cost: \u20ac850,000 (buildings acc dep \u20ac55,000)\n- Vehicles at cost: \u20ac440,000 (acc dep \u20ac75,000)\n- Patent 01/01/2023: \u20ac37,500\n- 3% Investments: \u20ac140,000\n- Purchases and sales: \u20ac1,500,000 / \u20ac2,150,000\n- Stock 01/01/2023: \u20ac57,000\n- Distribution costs: \u20ac232,000\n- Administration expenses: \u20ac146,000\n- Rental income: \u20ac85,000\n- Profit on sale of land: \u20ac60,000\n- 8% Debentures 2027/2028: \u20ac380,000\n\nAdjustments:\n(i) Closing stock \u20ac85,000\n(ii) Patent acquired 01/01/2018 for \u20ac75,000, amortised over 10 years, included in cost of sales\n(iii) Land sold for \u20ac270,000 (cost \u20ac210,000). Buildings dep 2% straight-line (25% distribution, 75% admin). Revalued at \u20ac950,000 at year end.\n(iv) Vehicles dep 20% of cost straight-line\n(v) Distribution costs includes receipt of \u20ac2,650 for patent royalties\n(vi) Provide for debenture interest, investment income, auditor's fees \u20ac8,500, corporation tax \u20ac87,000\n\nRequired:\n(a) Published P&L account for year ended 31/12/2023 with notes:\n1. Accounting policy note\n2. Operating profit\n3. Dividends\n4. Tangible fixed assets (52)\n(b)(i) Explain exceptional items with reference to Lyne plc (ii) Regulations for published statements (8)\n(60 marks)", a:"KEY ANSWERS:\n\nPublished P&L:\n- Turnover: \u20ac2,150,000\n- Cost of Sales: \u20ac1,479,500 (57,000 + 1,500,000 + 7,500 - 85,000)\n- Gross Profit: \u20ac670,500\n- Distribution Costs: \u20ac330,400 (232,000 + 4,500 + 2,650 + 88,000 + 3,250)\n- Administrative Expenses: \u20ac199,250 (146,000 + 35,000 + 8,500 + 9,750)\n- Other Operating Income: \u20ac101,650 (85,000 + 14,000 + 2,650)\n- Operating Profit: \u20ac242,500\n- Profit on sale of land: \u20ac60,000\n- Investment Income: \u20ac4,200 (140,000 x 3%)\n- Debenture Interest: (\u20ac30,400) (380,000 x 8%)\n- Profit before tax: \u20ac276,300\n- Corporation Tax: (\u20ac87,000)\n- Profit after tax: \u20ac189,300\n- Dividends: (\u20ac35,000)\n- Retained earnings: \u20ac154,300\n- P&L balance: \u20ac197,300\n\nDepreciation workings:\n- Buildings: 2% x \u20ac650,000 = \u20ac13,000 (distribution 25% = \u20ac3,250; admin 75% = \u20ac9,750)\n- Vehicles: 20% x \u20ac440,000 = \u20ac88,000\n- Patent amortisation: \u20ac75,000/10 = \u20ac7,500 (in cost of sales)\n\nNotes:\n1. Accounting Policy: Buildings revalued at end of 2023. Vehicles at cost. Buildings dep 2% straight-line, vehicles 20% straight-line. Stock valued at lower of cost and NRV (FIFO).\n2. Operating Profit after charging: Depreciation \u20ac101,000, Patent amortised \u20ac7,500, Directors remuneration \u20ac35,000, Auditors fees \u20ac8,500\n3. Dividends: Ordinary paid 5.8c per share \u20ac29,000; Preference paid 4.0c per share \u20ac6,000\n4. Tangible Fixed Assets note showing cost/revaluation, disposals, depreciation, NBV\n\n(b)(i) An exceptional item is a material item of significant size shown separately in the P&L. In Lyne plc, the profit on sale of land (\u20ac60,000) is an exceptional item.\n(b)(ii) Accountants must comply with: Government legislation, EU Directives, Accounting Standards Board (FRS's and SSAP's), Stock Exchange listing rules.\n\nWhy: Published accounts follow the Companies Act format. Cost of sales includes patent amortisation. The revaluation at year end requires a tangible fixed assets note showing the transfer of accumulated depreciation to the revaluation reserve."},
    {num:4, label:"Q3: Farm Accounts (E. Fleming)", q:"E. Fleming carries on a small mixed farming business. Assets on 01/01/2023 include:\nLand and buildings cost \u20ac410,000; vehicles/machinery cost \u20ac168,000; cattle value \u20ac88,000; sheep value \u20ac35,600; milk cheque due \u20ac6,900; stock of fuel \u20ac370; 2 months investment interest due \u20ac400.\n\nAll fixed assets have 3 years accumulated depreciation on 01/01/2023.\n\nCheque payments and lodgements summary provided for year.\nKey items: Milk receipts \u20ac100,000; Sheep sales \u20ac15,400; Cattle sales \u20ac14,900; Fertiliser \u20ac35,600; Light/heat/fuel \u20ac46,850; Loan repayment plus 18 months interest at 5% = \u20ac32,250.\n\nClosing values: Cattle \u20ac94,000; Sheep \u20ac51,000.\nFarm produce used: milk \u20ac550, lamb \u20ac770.\nFertiliser split 70:30 cattle:sheep. General expenses split 70:30.\n\nDepreciation: Buildings 2% (land \u20ac200,000), machinery 10%, no vehicles purchased.\n\nRequired:\n(a) Statement of Capital 01/01/2023 (20)\n(b) Enterprise Analysis - Cattle and Milk (20)\n(c) Enterprise Analysis - Sheep (12)\n(d) General P&L for year ended 31/12/2023 (8)\n(e) Advice on solar panel investment of \u20ac100,000 (8)\n(60 marks)", a:"KEY ANSWERS:\n\n(a) Statement of Capital 01/01/2023:\nAssets: L&B \u20ac410,000 less dep \u20ac12,600 = \u20ac397,400; Motor vehicles \u20ac168,000 less dep \u20ac50,400 = \u20ac117,600; Medicine prepaid \u20ac330; Cattle \u20ac88,000; Sheep \u20ac35,600; Milk due \u20ac6,900; Fuel \u20ac370; Investment income due \u20ac400; Investments \u20ac120,000; Bank \u20ac51,500 = \u20ac818,100\nLiabilities: ESB due \u20ac250; Loan \u20ac30,000; Loan interest due \u20ac1,250 = \u20ac31,500\nCapital: \u20ac786,600\n\n(b) Cattle and Milk Enterprise:\nIncome: Milk \u20ac100,050; Cattle and calves \u20ac25,700; Drawings \u20ac550; Increase in cattle value \u20ac6,000; Single payment \u20ac3,385 = \u20ac135,685\nExpenditure: Dairy wages \u20ac5,200; Fertiliser \u20ac25,445; General farm expenses \u20ac15,127; Cattle purchases \u20ac11,200; Vet fees \u20ac1,925 = \u20ac58,897\nGross Profit: \u20ac76,788\n\n(c) Sheep Enterprise:\nIncome: Sheep and lambs \u20ac24,100; Single payment \u20ac6,600; Wool \u20ac800; Drawings \u20ac770; Increase in value \u20ac15,400 = \u20ac47,670\nExpenditure: Fertiliser \u20ac10,905; General expenses \u20ac6,483; Sheep purchases \u20ac8,900; Vet fees \u20ac825 = \u20ac27,113\nProfit on Sheep: \u20ac20,557\n\n(d) General P&L:\nGross Profit Cattle \u20ac76,788 + Sheep \u20ac20,557 + Investment interest \u20ac2,400 + EU Glas \u20ac5,600 = \u20ac105,345\nLess: Light/heat/fuel \u20ac41,868; Repairs \u20ac5,175; Dep machinery \u20ac16,470; Dep buildings \u20ac3,780; Interest \u20ac900 = \u20ac68,193\nNet Profit: \u20ac37,152\n\n(e) Recommend installing solar panels. Light/heat bill would be reduced significantly per annum. Investment of \u20ac100,000 would be recovered in approximately 6 years. The farm can afford it with \u20ac32,605 in bank and \u20ac120,000 in investments.\n\nWhy: Farm accounts split expenses between enterprises (cattle/sheep). The loan calculation: \u20ac32,250/1.075 = \u20ac30,000 principal. Interest = \u20ac2,250 total for 18 months, but only 80% is business (private use 10% for light/heat, some for interest). Investment = \u20ac400/(2/12) x (1/0.02) = \u20ac120,000."},
    {num:5, label:"Q4: Correction of Errors or Depreciation", q:"Section 1 question (60 marks). In 2024, Question 4 was in Section 1 covering a topic such as correction of errors, depreciation of fixed assets, or similar financial accounting topic.\n\nTypical question structures:\n- Journal entries to correct errors\n- Suspense account\n- Corrected profit statement\n- Theory questions on purpose of trial balance or types of errors\n\nOR\n\n- Fixed asset accounts over multiple years\n- Provision for depreciation accounts\n- Disposal accounts\n- Theory on why depreciation is charged\n(60 marks)", a:"Students should be prepared for:\n\nCorrection of Errors:\n- Identify the original incorrect entry\n- Determine the correct entry\n- Write the correcting journal entry\n- Update the suspense account if the error affected the trial balance\n- Calculate the corrected profit\n\nDepreciation:\n- Straight-line: (Cost - Residual Value) / Useful Life\n- Reducing balance: Rate x Net Book Value\n- Date-based calculations: prorate for part-year ownership\n- Disposal: Cost to disposal a/c, accumulated depreciation to disposal a/c, proceeds to disposal a/c, profit/loss to P&L\n\nWhy: Errors in bookkeeping must be corrected through proper journal entries before final accounts are prepared. Depreciation matches the cost of using an asset against the revenue it generates over its useful life (matching principle)."},
    {num:6, label:"Q5: Interpretation of Accounts or Club Accounts", q:"Section 2 question (100 marks). Candidates answer two from Q5, Q6, Q7.\n\nInterpretation of Accounts typically requires:\n- Calculating 5 ratios from given financial statements\n- Analysing profitability, liquidity, dividend policy, and gearing\n- Comparing year-on-year performance\n- Making recommendations to shareholders\n\nClub Accounts typically requires:\n- Accumulated fund (opening capital)\n- Receipts and payments account analysis\n- Income and expenditure account\n- Bar trading account\n- Theory on club accounting\n(100 marks)", a:"Key Interpretation Ratios:\n- ROCE: measures efficiency of capital use\n- EPS: earnings attributable to each ordinary share\n- P/E Ratio: how many years to recover share price from earnings\n- Dividend Cover: how many times dividends are covered by profits\n- Dividend Yield: return on investment at current market price\n- Acid Test: ability to pay short-term debts without selling stock\n- Gearing: proportion of long-term debt to total capital\n\nClub Accounts Key Points:\n- Accumulated fund = Opening assets - Opening liabilities\n- Income and expenditure uses accruals basis (not cash basis)\n- Subscriptions: adjust for arrears and prepaid\n- Life membership spread over agreed period\n- Bar trading: separate account for trading activities\n\nWhy: Interpretation questions test analytical skills. Club accounts differ from business accounts because clubs are not-for-profit organisations - they prepare income and expenditure accounts, not profit and loss accounts."},
    {num:7, label:"Q8/Q9: Management Accounting", q:"Section 3 question (80 marks). Candidates answer one of Q8 or Q9.\n\n2024 management accounting topics could include:\n- Marginal Costing and Break-Even Analysis\n- Cash Budget preparation\n- Product Costing\n- Absorption Costing\n- Decision-making (special orders, make vs buy)\n\nBreak-even questions typically provide:\n- Selling price per unit\n- Variable costs per unit\n- Fixed costs\n- Current production levels\n\nStudents must calculate break-even point, margin of safety, and profit at various activity levels.\n(80 marks)", a:"Management Accounting Key Concepts:\n\nBreak-Even Analysis:\n- Contribution per unit = Selling price - Variable cost per unit\n- Break-even units = Fixed costs / Contribution per unit\n- Break-even revenue = Fixed costs / (Contribution/Sales ratio)\n- Margin of Safety = Current sales - Break-even sales\n- For target profit: Units = (Fixed costs + Target profit) / Contribution per unit\n\nCash Budget:\n- Start with opening cash balance\n- Add all cash receipts (cash sales, credit collections, other income)\n- Deduct all cash payments (purchases, wages, expenses, capital items)\n- Calculate closing balance each month\n- Credit sales collections often lagged (e.g., 1 month credit)\n\nAbsorption Costing:\n- Total cost = Direct materials + Direct labour + Variable overheads + Fixed overheads\n- Overhead absorption rate = Total overheads / Activity level\n- Under/over absorption = Absorbed overheads - Actual overheads\n\nWhy: Break-even analysis is critical for understanding the minimum sales volume needed to cover costs. Cash budgets help businesses plan for cash shortfalls and arrange finance in advance."}
  ]
};
